ial sex workers but resist HIV testing for fear of threatening their economic and political status. Their fate is further complicated by a political system that cannot publicly acknowledge such risk and by authoritative international paradigms that limit the reach of public health interventions. Ultimately, Uretsky offers insights into how complex socio-cultural and politico-economic negotiations affect the development and administration of China's HIV epidemic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aBusinessmenxSexual behaviorxChina. 0aBusinessmenxSexual behaviorzChina. 0aHIV infectionsxSocial aspectsxChina. 0aHIV infectionsxSocial aspectszChina. 0aMasculinityxChina. 0aMasculinityzChina. 0aSocial networksxChina. 0aSocial networkszChina. 4aChina. 4aHIV/AIDS. 4agovernance. 4agovernmentality. 4amasculinity. 4apublic health. 4asexuality. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479756640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797566423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797566.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles